SIMPLE: sensationalism
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Sensationalism
<hw>Sen*sa"tion*al*ism</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn>
<fld>(Metaph.)</fld> <def>The doctrine held by Condillac, and by some
ascribed to Locke, that our ideas originate solely in sensation, and
consist of sensations transformed; sensualism; -- opposed to
<contr>intuitionalism</contr>, and <contr>rationalism</contr>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The practice or methods of sensational writing or
speaking; <as>as, the <ex>sensationalism</ex> of a novel</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sensationalist</ent>⟦br⟧
